# LaTeX Presentation

Distinctive Beamer slides. Not the default theme, not a wall of bullets.

## Theme Setup

Start with a clean base and customize:

```latex
\documentclass[aspectratio=169]{beamer}
\usetheme{default}
\usecolortheme{default}

% Remove navigation symbols
\setbeamertemplate{navigation symbols}{}

% Clean frame title
\setbeamertemplate{frametitle}{
  \vspace{0.5em}
  \insertframetitle
}

% Custom colors
\definecolor{primary}{HTML}{2D3436}
\definecolor{accent}{HTML}{0984E3}
\definecolor{muted}{HTML}{636E72}
\definecolor{bg}{HTML}{FAFAFA}

\setbeamercolor{title}{fg=primary}
\setbeamercolor{frametitle}{fg=primary}
\setbeamercolor{normal text}{fg=primary, bg=bg}
\setbeamercolor{itemize item}{fg=accent}
\setbeamercolor{itemize subitem}{fg=muted}
```

## Slide Structure

### Title slide
```latex
\begin{frame}
  \vfill
  \centering
  {\Large\bfseries\inserttitle}\\[0.5em]
  {\color{muted}\insertauthor}\\[0.3em]
  {\color{muted}\small\insertdate}
  \vfill
\end{frame}
```

### Content slide
```latex
\begin{frame}{Slide Title}
  % Maximum 3-4 points per slide
  \begin{itemize}
    \item First point - the key insight
    \item Second point - supporting evidence
    \item Third point - implication
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}
```

### Two-column slide
```latex
\begin{frame}{Comparison}
  \begin{columns}[T]
    \begin{column}{0.48\textwidth}
      \textbf{Approach A}
      \begin{itemize}
        \item Pro 1
        \item Pro 2
      \end{itemize}
    \end{column}
    \begin{column}{0.48\textwidth}
      \textbf{Approach B}
      \begin{itemize}
        \item Pro 1
        \item Pro 2
      \end{itemize}
    \end{column}
  \end{columns}
\end{frame}
```

## Charts with pgfplots

```latex
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

% Chart style
\pgfplotsset{
  every axis/.append style={
    font=\small,
    tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
    label style={font=\small},
    legend style={font=\footnotesize, draw=none, fill=none},
    axis line style={draw=muted},
    tick style={draw=muted},
    grid style={draw=muted!20},
    major grid style={draw=muted!30},
  }
}
```

### Bar chart
```latex
\begin{frame}{Results}
  \centering
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
      ybar, width=0.8\textwidth, height=0.6\textheight,
      bar width=20pt,
      symbolic x coords={A, B, C, D},
      xtick=data, ymajorgrids=true,
      ylabel={Score (\%)},
      ymin=0, ymax=100,
      nodes near coords, nodes near coords align={vertical},
    ]
      \addplot[fill=accent, draw=none] coordinates {(A,85) (B,72) (C,91) (D,68)};
    \end{axis}
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{frame>
```

### Line chart
```latex
\begin{frame}{Trend}
  \centering
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
      width=0.8\textwidth, height=0.6\textheight,
      xlabel={Time}, ylabel={Value},
      xmajorgrids=true, ymajorgrids=true,
      legend pos=north west,
    ]
      \addplot[accent, thick, mark=*] coordinates {(1,10) (2,15) (3,12) (4,20) (5,25)};
      \addlegendentry{Method A}
      \addplot[muted, thick, mark=square*] coordinates {(1,8) (2,11) (3,14) (4,16) (5,19)};
      \addlegendentry{Method B}
    \end{axis}
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{frame}
```

## Speaker Notes

```latex
\usepackage{pgfpages}
\setbeameroption{show notes on second screen=right}

\begin{frame}{Key Finding}
  Our method outperforms the baseline by 15\%.
  \note{
    Emphasize that this is on the held-out test set.
    Mention that the baseline was tuned with the same budget.
    If asked about statistical significance: p < 0.01, paired t-test.
  }
\end{frame}
```

## Typography Rules

- **Maximum**: 6 lines of text per slide, 8 words per line
- **Font size**: minimum 18pt for body text, 14pt for footnotes
- **Hierarchy**: title (28-32pt) > subtitle (22-24pt) > body (18-20pt)
- **Emphasis**: `\textbf{}` for key terms, `\color{accent}` for highlights. Never underline.
- **No**: full sentences on slides. Use fragments. Speak the full sentence.

## Anti-Examples

| Bad | Why | Better |
|-----|-----|--------|
| Default Beamer theme (Warsaw, etc.) | Instantly recognizable as "generic academic talk" | Custom minimal theme |
| 10 bullet points per slide | Nobody reads them | 3-4 points maximum, speak the rest |
| Reading slides verbatim | Audience reads faster than you speak | Slides show key points, you provide context |
| Tiny charts with no labels | Unintelligible from the back row | Large charts, clear labels, minimum 14pt font |
| Animation on every element | Distracting, slows the talk | Animate only when reveal order matters |

## Quality Self-Check

1. Every slide passes the "3-second test" (audience gets the point in 3 seconds)?
2. Charts readable from the back of the room?
3. Maximum 3-4 points per slide?
4. Color palette consistent throughout?
5. Speaker notes for complex or data-heavy slides?
